rmk:
Habitat and Location: Damp area undergrowth along a stream and small water catchment for a new resort. Mile 1 Natmataung NP. 

Behaviour: Playback used. The Pygmy joined in the chorus of a Chin HIlls Wren-babbler circling the immediate vicinity XC133360. Chin Hills changed song when the Pygmy was singing. In retrospect, I could have been disturbing an unseen nest as this is breeding season for many of the residents. 

The two of them continued for several minutes as a duet XC133362, as if advertising to the other a claim to the same choice spot.

Recording information: No modification to the call was done.
Habitat: Montane mossy forest
Behavior: One bird was seen feeding in the mossy undergrowth, below a female snowy-browed flycatcher. It was not calling until we identified it as a pygmy wren babbler and played its 3-note song. However, the bird responded with this call instead and subsequently, we only heard this call along the trail and identified them to be made by the pygmy wren babbler.

Pareja de elanio azul que cría en un olivar avandonado cerca del pueblo, lugar que la gente usa para pasear y sacar sus mascotas. Los audios se han obtenido colocando pequeñas grabadoras en las atalayas donde el macho ofrece presas a la hembra con las que alimentar a sus cuatro pollos ya crecidos pero qúe aún están en el nido.

Pareja de elanios grabada colocando pequeñas grabadoras en sus atalayas de cortejo donde copulan y el macho ofrece presas a la hembra. El hábitat es una finca de olivos avandonada junto a una que sí se encuentra en explotación. La gente del pueblo va allí a pasear y sacar sus mascotas. En el lugar hay una buena población de roedores de los que viven estas aves.
Bird seen calling from the top of a thorn tree in the early morning while another one was flying around the area.

Pareja en cortejo. Grabación obtenida por audiotrampeo en un bosquete de árboles hornamentales que se encuentra cerca de un olivar. Más allá hay un arroyo tupido de zarzas y con algunos álamos, además de un campo de cereales. Este bosquecillo hornamental pertenecía a un hotel rural que fracasó pero los árboles se han quedado allí.

rmk: A very nice series of combination with calls and songs. The main call is around 4500-8000Hz (but with a note having a spike-down to 2500Hz), and the 1-note type or the double-note type is both quite common. The song is mainly between 3000-6000Hz with around 7-17 notes. There is also some interesting murmurs that can be heard between 00:50-01:50. The main target is recorded and sighted within 3 meters, and there is another individual around 30-50 meters away in the background (but probably came near in the last 10-20 seconds.)

rmk: gaps between successive groups of notes are frequently of x+x/2 beats; in other words, after a series of notes on a regular beat, the next series of notes will start on the offbeat, then the following will start on the offbeat of that - so back to the original onbeat, at least roughly; this is not true of all sets of vocalisations, but it is a very common feature; I also noticed this occurring with Singaporean subspecies bimaculatus

rmk:
Habitat and Location: Damp area undergrowth along a stream and small water catchment for a new resort. Mile 1 Natmataung NP. 

Behaviour: Playback used. The Pygmy joined in the chorus of a Chin HIlls Wren-babbler circling the immediate vicinity XC133360. Chin Hills changed song when the Pygmy was singing. In retrospect, I could have been disturbing an unseen nest as this is breeding season for many of the residents. 

The two of them continued for several minutes as a duet XC133362, as if advertising to the other a claim to the same choice spot.

Recording information: No modification to the call was done.
Habitat: Montane mossy forest
Behavior: One bird was seen feeding in the mossy undergrowth, below a female snowy-browed flycatcher. It was not calling until we identified it as a pygmy wren babbler and played its 3-note song. However, the bird responded with this call instead and subsequently, we only heard this call along the trail and identified them to be made by the pygmy wren babbler.

El ecosistema consiste en un arroyo seco en la mayor parte de su recorrido, pero la cercanía del nivel freático a la superficie permite la existencia de bosques de álamo, tarajales y carrizal que aunque han sido eliminados en gran parte aún quedan fragmentos. Más allá hay un mosaico de pinar, olivares, algunos restos de alcornocal-encinar, viñedos y cultivos de leguminosas y cereal.

As much noise as possible was removed. It was right along main road to Jouberton location with heavy traffic. They were in a row of exotic fir trees on the way to the sewerage works. First a high pitched "peep" "peep". Apparently the female calling the male. Then the male flies in and their is high-pitched "weeugh" sounds. The passing traffic interrupts the recording badly.

Sukau Barefoot Lodge, Kinabatangan River, Borneo:

I was on a river tour to search for pygmy elephants. We encountered a small herd crossing the big river. When we encountered the small herd, I filmed a short video near the shore from the small river boat.

Tropical vegetation lined the river banks. Tall grass had attracted the herd.

In the background a bird was singing. In the foreground, some guests were excitedly talking about their observations.

It's important for me to acknowledge that Jelle Scharringa did the ID for me.

Many thanks,

rmk: A very nice series of combination with calls and songs. The main call is around 4500-8000Hz (but with a note having a spike-down to 2500Hz), and the 1-note type or the double-note type is both quite common. The song is mainly between 3000-6000Hz with around 7-17 notes. There is also some interesting murmurs that can be heard between 00:50-01:50. The main target is recorded and sighted within 3 meters, and there is another individual around 30-50 meters away in the background (but probably came near in the last 10-20 seconds.)

A total of five different individuals calling in this recording. One male and two females seen. Other two birds not seen but were very close by. The two females seen were perched on the same tree, calling while flicking their tails up and down. One of them was more vocal than the other and also cocked its head up and down while calling. The more vocal bird seemed slightly bigger than the other in the field and kept approaching the other bird by hopping towards it, but the other less vocal bird kept hopping away. The birds eventually flew off and I was unable to continue my observation.

rmk: The Asian Koel (Eudynamys scolopaceus) is a member of the cuckoo order of birds, the Cuculiformes. It is found in South Asia, China, and Southeast Asia. It forms a superspecies with the closely related Black-billed and Pacific Koels which are sometimes treated as subspecies. The Asian Koel is a brood parasite that lays its eggs in the nests of crows and other hosts, who raise its young. They are unusual among the cuckoos in being largely frugivorous as adults. The name koel is echoic in origin with several language variants. The Asian Koel is a large, long-tailed, cuckoo measuring 39–46 cm (15–18 in) and weighing 190–327 g (6.7–11.5 oz). The male of the nominate race is glossy bluish-black, with a pale greenish grey bill, the iris is crimson, and it has grey legs and feet. The female of the nominate race is brownish on the crown and has rufous streaks on the head. The back, rump and wing coverts are dark brown with white and buff spots. The underparts are whitish, but is heavily striped. The other subspecies differ in colouration and size. The upper plumage of young birds is more like that of the male and they have a black beak. They are very vocal during the breeding season (March to August in South Asia), with a range of different calls. The familiar song of the male is a repeated koo-Ooo. The female makes a shrill kik-kik-kik... call. Calls vary across populations. The Asian Koel is a bird of light woodland and cultivation. It is a mainly resident breeder in tropical southern Asia from India and Sri Lanka to south China and the Greater Sundas. They have great potential in colonizing new areas, and were among the pioneer birds to colonize the volcanic island of Krakatau. They first arrived in Singapore in the 1980s and became very common birds. Some populations may make long distance movements.

rmk: gaps between successive groups of notes are frequently of x+x/2 beats; in other words, after a series of notes on a regular beat, the next series of notes will start on the offbeat, then the following will start on the offbeat of that - so back to the original onbeat, at least roughly; this is not true of all sets of vocalisations, but it is a very common feature; I also noticed this occurring with Singaporean subspecies bimaculatus

4 poussins à l'envol

Grabado en un olivar cerca de un tramo de arroyo con cañas.

El ecosistema consiste en un arroyo seco en la mayor parte de su recorrido, pero la cercanía del nivel freático a la superficie permite la existencia de bosques de álamo, tarajales y carrizal que aunque han sido eliminados en gran parte aún quedan fragmentos. Más allá hay un mosaico de pinar, olivares, algunos restos de alcornocal-encinar, viñedos y cultivos de leguminosas y cereal.

loc: JB Marks Local Municipality, Southern DC, North West
rmk: Very short call in flight.

As much noise as possible was removed. It was right along main road to Jouberton location with heavy traffic. They were in a row of exotic fir trees on the way to the sewerage works. First a high pitched "peep" "peep". Apparently the female calling the male. Then the male flies in and their is high-pitched "weeugh" sounds. The passing traffic interrupts the recording badly.

I was on a river tour to search for pygmy elephants. We encountered a small herd crossing the big river. When we encountered the small herd, I filmed a short video near the shore from the small river boat.

Tropical vegetation lined the river banks. Tall grass had attracted the herd.

It's important for me to acknowledge that Jelle Scharringa did the ID for me.

Many thanks,

rmk: A very nice series of combination with calls and songs. The main call is around 4500-8000Hz (but with a note having a spike-down to 2500Hz), and the 1-note type or the double-note type is both quite common. The song is mainly between 3000-6000Hz with around 7-17 notes. There is also some interesting murmurs that can be heard between 00:50-01:50. The main target is recorded and sighted within 3 meters, and there is another individual around 30-50 meters away in the background (but probably came near in the last 10-20 seconds.)

A total of five different individuals calling in this recording. One male and two females seen. Other two birds not seen but were very close by. The two females seen were perched on the same tree, calling while flicking their tails up and down. One of them was more vocal than the other and also cocked its head up and down while calling. The more vocal bird seemed slightly bigger than the other in the field and kept approaching the other bird by hopping towards it, but the other less vocal bird kept hopping away. The birds eventually flew off and I was unable to continue my observation.

This recording was taken at the same area as that in the recording by me from 26 March 2020. There were several (3+) individuals of Asian Koels around the same area but it might be the same individual.

rmk: The Asian Koel (Eudynamys scolopaceus) is a member of the cuckoo order of birds, the Cuculiformes. It is found in South Asia, China, and Southeast Asia. It forms a superspecies with the closely related Black-billed and Pacific Koels which are sometimes treated as subspecies. The Asian Koel is a brood parasite that lays its eggs in the nests of crows and other hosts, who raise its young. They are unusual among the cuckoos in being largely frugivorous as adults. The name koel is echoic in origin with several language variants. The Asian Koel is a large, long-tailed, cuckoo measuring 39–46 cm (15–18 in) and weighing 190–327 g (6.7–11.5 oz). The male of the nominate race is glossy bluish-black, with a pale greenish grey bill, the iris is crimson, and it has grey legs and feet. The female of the nominate race is brownish on the crown and has rufous streaks on the head. The back, rump and wing coverts are dark brown with white and buff spots. The underparts are whitish, but is heavily striped. The other subspecies differ in colouration and size. The upper plumage of young birds is more like that of the male and they have a black beak. They are very vocal during the breeding season (March to August in South Asia), with a range of different calls. The familiar song of the male is a repeated koo-Ooo. The female makes a shrill kik-kik-kik... call. Calls vary across populations. The Asian Koel is a bird of light woodland and cultivation. It is a mainly resident breeder in tropical southern Asia from India and Sri Lanka to south China and the Greater Sundas. They have great potential in colonizing new areas, and were among the pioneer birds to colonize the volcanic island of Krakatau. They first arrived in Singapore in the 1980s and became very common birds. Some populations may make long distance movements.
